explanation:
- OS_NetworkGetID_Impl: The target function delegates its work to this implementation. To determine whether memcmp is used to compare NUL-terminated strings you must inspect the body of this function and any functions it calls.
- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType: Appears as a direct callee in the static call graph for the target; the test-stub implementation could itself call memcmp (or call other helpers that do), so it must be checked.
- UT_ExecuteBasicHandler: Direct callee in the graph; its implementation or the handlers it invokes could use memcmp for string comparisons.
- UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: Direct callee in the graph; may call helper functions that perform comparisons — inspect it for memcmp usage.
- UT_GetStubEntry: Callee of the UT_* stubs above; included so the full stub-call chain can be examined for any memcmp usage.
- UT_ClearStubEntry: Callee of UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType; included to trace stub internals for memcmp usages.
- UtAssert_Abort: Callee referenced by stubs; included because assertion helpers sometimes format/compare strings — must be scanned for memcmp usage.
- UT_SetHandlerFunction: Callee of UT_ExecuteBasicHandler; included to inspect handler-setting code for memcmp usage.
- UT_DefaultStubImpl: Callee of UT_ExecuteBasicHandler; the default stub implementation may perform comparisons — inspect for memcmp.
- UtAssert_GetContext: Callee of UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr chain; included to complete the stub/assertion call chain.
- memcmp: The standard library function that MISRA forbids for comparing null-terminated strings; include this symbol so the analyzer can directly detect any use (direct or indirect) of memcmp in the target or any reachable callee.

Rationale: The MISRA rule is violated only if memcmp is used to compare null-terminated strings in the target or any function it calls (directly or via the stub/handler chain present in the call graph). The list includes the implementation the target delegates to plus the direct stub/handler callees and their immediate callees so the analyser can trace any occurrence of memcmp within the complete reachable call set.
